Higher levels of CO2 tend to prevent histamine release. Spring is probably a good time to experiment with bag breathing or baking soda baths if you have spring allergies to see what the interaction will be like.

Lowering histamine itself slows the rate of breathing down, which probably means mechanically filtering out more allergens out of the air breathed in. So it's either a vicious or a virtuous cycle. La Rochefoucauld or Leibniz.

In the second book of Gene Wolfe's BoTNS, the worst punishment in the town of Saltus was being walled inside your home and left to ferment in the darkness. This is basically exactly how Peat describes darkness-stress and melatonin: whiteness, hypersensitivity to light, blindness.

Alcohol lowers melatonin, that's why people drink more spirits in winter (or in Russia), when nights are long. If you are trapped in a dark cave with a few crates of good white rum bottles, you will become an alcoholic, but won't turn into Gollum.

Peat calls journalists, scientists, etc. the opposite of paranoiacs, "anti-paranoia", a state with the clichees of expert trusting, nothing ever happens, etc. It's logical then that this state lacks all the benefits of paranoia. It will always assume a stale state, tiresomeness.

Dr. Ray Peat literally quotes Salvador Dali (another visionary, see also "Paranoiac-critical method") on paranoia being a "positive" state, that always comes with creativity, intuitive associative thinking.

Thus even if e.g. conservatard boomers overshoot and end up with some wacky theory about Q arriving with Ivermectin on Trump's second inauguration, it always is exciting, active. But libtardists can be correct and it still won't matter, because it will be grapes dried on the vine
